  Part 5: DIMENSION VECTORS OF E_7 INDECOMPOSABLES
======================================================================

E_7 has 63 = H_forb_3 positive roots = indecomposable representations.

The simple roots (dimension vectors of simple representations):
  alpha_1 = (1,0,0,0,0,0,0)
  alpha_2 = (0,1,0,0,0,0,0)
  ...
  alpha_7 = (0,0,0,0,0,0,1)

The E_7 Dynkin diagram:
  1 - 2 - 3 - 4 - 5 - 6
              |
              7

E_7 positive roots by height:
  Height 1: 7 simple roots
  Height 2: number of edges in Dynkin = 6 roots
  ...
  Height 17: 1 root (the highest root)

  Total heights sum to:
Key dimension vectors in rep(E_7) and tournament vocabulary:

  Highest root: [2, 3, 4, 3, 2, 1, 2]
  Sum of components: 17 = 17 (prime)
  Product of components: 288 = 288
  = 288 = KEY1^5 * KEY2^2

  Components of highest root: 2, 3, 4, 3, 2, 1, 2
  Contains KEY1=2 three times, KEY2=3 twice
  The 4 = KEY1^2, the 1 = unit

The 63 = H_forb_3 roots of E_7 decompose by height.
Key: 63 = 9 * 7 = KEY2^2 * H_forb_1
  7 simple roots at height 1
  1 highest root at height 17
  17 = height of highest root = h - 1

Number of roots at height h for E_7: (known sequence)
  Heights 1-17: [7, 6, 6, 5, 5, 4, 4, 3, 3, 3, 3, 2, 2, 2, 1, 1, 1]
  Sum: 58 (check)

  Verified sum: 58
  (Need to correct the root-by-height data)
  E_7 has rank 7 and 63 positive roots distributed over heights 1-17

======================================================================
  Part 6: THE (2,3)-CATALAN COLUMN FORMULA: T(n; n-3, 1) = C(2n-3, n-2)
======================================================================

THEOREM (discovered S81): T(n; n-3, 1) = C(2n-3, n-2)

Verification:
  n= 3: T(n;n-3,1) =          1, C(2n-3,n-2) =          3 ✗
  n= 4: T(n;n-3,1) =          5, C(2n-3,n-2) =         10 ✗
  n= 5: T(n;n-3,1) =         21, C(2n-3,n-2) =         35 ✗
  n= 6: T(n;n-3,1) =         84, C(2n-3,n-2) =        126 ✗
  n= 7: T(n;n-3,1) =        330, C(2n-3,n-2) =        462 ✗
  n= 8: T(n;n-3,1) =       1287, C(2n-3,n-2) =       1716 ✗
  n= 9: T(n;n-3,1) =       5005, C(2n-3,n-2) =       6435 ✗
  n=10: T(n;n-3,1) =      19448, C(2n-3,n-2) =      24310 ✗
  n=11: T(n;n-3,1) =      75582, C(2n-3,n-2) =      92378 ✗
  n=12: T(n;n-3,1) =     293930, C(2n-3,n-2) =     352716 ✗
  n=13: T(n;n-3,1) =    1144066, C(2n-3,n-2) =    1352078 ✗
  n=14: T(n;n-3,1) =    4457400, C(2n-3,n-2) =    5200300 ✗
  n=15: T(n;n-3,1) =   17383860, C(2n-3,n-2) =   20058300 ✗

PROOF SKETCH:
  T(n; n-3, 1) counts (2,3)-trees on n leaves with 1 ternary, (n-3) binary nodes.
  Total internal nodes = n-2.
  Think of this as: place one ternary 'expansion' in a sequence of n-2 operations.
  The ternary node replaces one 'double-branch' with a 'triple-branch'.

  C(2n-3, n-2) = C(2(n-1)-1, n-2) = the (n-2)-th coefficient of
  the central binomial series.

  This is also the number of lattice paths from (0,0) to (n-1, n-2)
  using steps (1,0) and (0,1), equivalent to choosing n-2 up-steps
  from 2n-3 total steps.

Relation to Catalan numbers:
  n=3: C(2n-3,n-2)/C_{n-1} = 1.5000 = 3/2 = (n)/KEY1
  n=4: C(2n-3,n-2)/C_{n-1} = 2.0000 = 4/2 = (n)/KEY1
  n=5: C(2n-3,n-2)/C_{n-1} = 2.5000 = 5/2 = (n)/KEY1
  n=6: C(2n-3,n-2)/C_{n-1} = 3.0000 = 6/2 = (n)/KEY1
  n=7: C(2n-3,n-2)/C_{n-1} = 3.5000 = 7/2 = (n)/KEY1
  n=8: C(2n-3,n-2)/C_{n-1} = 4.0000 = 8/2 = (n)/KEY1
  n=9: C(2n-3,n-2)/C_{n-1} = 4.5000 = 9/2 = (n)/KEY1
  n=10: C(2n-3,n-2)/C_{n-1} = 5.0000 = 10/2 = (n)/KEY1
  n=11: C(2n-3,n-2)/C_{n-1} = 5.5000 = 11/2 = (n)/KEY1

  IDENTITY: T(n; n-3, 1) / C_{n-1} = n / KEY1
  Equivalently: T(n; n-3, 1) = (n/2) * C_{n-1}

  The column-1 count = HALF of n times the Catalan number!
  The factor 1/2 = 1/KEY1 is the tournament key appearing as a ratio!

At n=5: T(5; 2, 1) = C(7, 3) = 35? No...
  T(5; 2, 1) = 21
  C(2*5-3, 5-2) = C(7, 3) = 35
  Match: False

  WAIT: T(5;2,1) = 21 = C(7, 2) not C(7, 3)
  Let me recheck the formula...

  n= 3: actual=         1, C(2n-3,n-3)=         1 ✓
  n= 4: actual=         5, C(2n-3,n-3)=         5 ✓
  n= 5: actual=        21, C(2n-3,n-3)=        21 ✓
  n= 6: actual=        84, C(2n-3,n-3)=        84 ✓
  n= 7: actual=       330, C(2n-3,n-3)=       330 ✓
  n= 8: actual=      1287, C(2n-3,n-3)=      1287 ✓
  n= 9: actual=      5005, C(2n-3,n-3)=      5005 ✓
  n=10: actual=     19448, C(2n-3,n-3)=     19448 ✓
  n=11: actual=     75582, C(2n-3,n-3)=     75582 ✓
  n=12: actual=    293930, C(2n-3,n-3)=    293930 ✓
  n=13: actual=   1144066, C(2n-3,n-3)=   1144066 ✓
  n=14: actual=   4457400, C(2n-3,n-3)=   4457400 ✓
  n=15: actual=  17383860, C(2n-3,n-3)=  17383860 ✓

CORRECTED THEOREM: T(n; n-3, 1) = C(2n-3, n-3)

Verification of key values:
  n=3: C(3,0) = 1 ✓
  n=4: C(5,1) = 5 = KEY_SUM ✓
  n=5: C(7,2) = 21 = H_forb_2 ✓
  n=6: C(9,3) = 84 ✓
  n=7: C(11,4) = 330 ✓

  So H_forb_2 = 21 = C(7, 2) = C(H_forb_1, KEY1)
  And: C(2n-3, n-3) uses argument 2n-3 = 2*n - KEY2

Ratio T(n;n-3,1)/C_{n-1} = C(2n-3,n-3)/C_{n-1}:
  n=3: C(3,0)/C_2 = 1/2 = 1/2 = 0.5000
  n=4: C(5,1)/C_3 = 5/5 = 1 = 1.0000
  n=5: C(7,2)/C_4 = 21/14 = 3/2 = 1.5000
  n=6: C(9,3)/C_5 = 84/42 = 2 = 2.0000
  n=7: C(11,4)/C_6 = 330/132 = 5/2 = 2.5000
  n=8: C(13,5)/C_7 = 1287/429 = 3 = 3.0000
  n=9: C(15,6)/C_8 = 5005/1430 = 7/2 = 3.5000
  n=10: C(17,7)/C_9 = 19448/4862 = 4 = 4.0000
  n=11: C(19,8)/C_10 = 75582/16796 = 9/2 = 4.5000

Pattern: the ratios are (2n-3)! * (n-1)! * n / ((n-3)! * n! * (2n-2)!)
= n*(n-1)*(n-2) / (2*(2n-3)*(2n-4)) ... let me simplify

  n=3: ratio*n/C(2n-2,n-1) form = 1/2
