  n=11: ratio*n/C(2n-2,n-1) form = 9/2

======================================================================
  Part 7: THE FORMULA T(n; n-3, 1) = C(2n-3, n-3) AND BALLOT NUMBERS
======================================================================

C(2n-3, n-3) is a BALLOT NUMBER!

The ballot number B(n, k) = (k+1)/(n+1) * C(n+1, (n-k)/2 + 1)
or equivalently, B(p, q) = (p-q+1)/(p+1) * C(p+1, q)

Our numbers C(2m+1, m) for m = n-3:
  m=0: C(1,0) = 1, C_m = 1, ratio = 1
  m=1: C(3,1) = 3, C_m = 1, ratio = 3
  m=2: C(5,2) = 10, C_m = 2, ratio = 5
  m=3: C(7,3) = 35, C_m = 5, ratio = 7
  m=4: C(9,4) = 126, C_m = 14, ratio = 9
  m=5: C(11,5) = 462, C_m = 42, ratio = 11
  m=6: C(13,6) = 1716, C_m = 132, ratio = 13
  m=7: C(15,7) = 6435, C_m = 429, ratio = 15

C(2m+1, m) = (2/(2m+1 choose m)) ... let me check:
  C(2m+1, m) / C_m = (2m+1)! * m! * (m+1)! / (m! * (m+1)! * (2m)!) = 2m+1 ... no

  m=0: val*(m+1)/C(2m,m) = 1
  m=1: val*(m+1)/C(2m,m) = 3
  m=2: val*(m+1)/C(2m,m) = 5
  m=3: val*(m+1)/C(2m,m) = 7
  m=4: val*(m+1)/C(2m,m) = 9
  m=5: val*(m+1)/C(2m,m) = 11
  m=6: val*(m+1)/C(2m,m) = 13
  m=7: val*(m+1)/C(2m,m) = 15

Identity: C(2m+1, m) = (2m+1)/(m+1) * C_m = (2m+1)!! / m!! ... 
  C(2m+1, m) = C(2m+1, m+1)
  And C_m = C(2m, m)/(m+1)
  So C(2m+1, m) / C_m = (m+1) * C(2m+1, m) / C(2m, m)
                       = (m+1) * (2m+1)! * m! / (m! * (m+1)! * (2m)!)
                       = (2m+1)! / ((m+1)! * (2m)! / m!)
  Hmm, let me just verify numerically.

  m=0: C(2m+1,m)/C_m = 1/1 = 1.0000 = (2*0+1)/1 = 1? True
    C(2m+1,m) = C(2m,m)*(2m+1)/(m+1) = 1*1 = 1
    = 1
    actual = 1
  m=1: C(2m+1,m)/C_m = 3/1 = 3.0000 = (2*1+1)/1 = 3? True
    C(2m+1,m) = C(2m,m)*(2m+1)/(m+1) = 2*3/2 = 3
    = 3
    actual = 3
  m=2: C(2m+1,m)/C_m = 10/2 = 5.0000 = (2*2+1)/1 = 5? True
    C(2m+1,m) = C(2m,m)*(2m+1)/(m+1) = 6*5/3 = 10
    = 10
    actual = 10
  m=3: C(2m+1,m)/C_m = 35/5 = 7.0000 = (2*3+1)/1 = 7? True
    C(2m+1,m) = C(2m,m)*(2m+1)/(m+1) = 20*7/4 = 35
    = 35
    actual = 35
  m=4: C(2m+1,m)/C_m = 126/14 = 9.0000 = (2*4+1)/1 = 9? True
    C(2m+1,m) = C(2m,m)*(2m+1)/(m+1) = 70*9/5 = 126
    = 126
    actual = 126
  m=5: C(2m+1,m)/C_m = 462/42 = 11.0000 = (2*5+1)/1 = 11? True
    C(2m+1,m) = C(2m,m)*(2m+1)/(m+1) = 252*11/6 = 462
    = 462
    actual = 462
  m=6: C(2m+1,m)/C_m = 1716/132 = 13.0000 = (2*6+1)/1 = 13? True
    C(2m+1,m) = C(2m,m)*(2m+1)/(m+1) = 924*13/7 = 1716
    = 1716
    actual = 1716
  m=7: C(2m+1,m)/C_m = 6435/429 = 15.0000 = (2*7+1)/1 = 15? True
    C(2m+1,m) = C(2m,m)*(2m+1)/(m+1) = 3432*15/8 = 6435
    = 6435
    actual = 6435

======================================================================
  Part 8: H_FORB_2 = 21 = C(7,2): THE BALLOT/BINOMIAL INTERPRETATION
======================================================================

H_forb_2 = 21 = T(5; 2, 1) = C(7, 2) = C(2*5-3, 5-3)

Interpretations of C(7, 2) = 21:
  1. Choose 2 items from 7 = |PG(2,2)| = |Fano|
  2. Triangular number T_6 = 6*7/2 = h(G2) * H_forb_1 / KEY1
  3. The 21 points of PG(2, 4) (projective plane over F_4)
  4. 21 = 3 * 7 = KEY2 * H_forb_1 = H_forb_1 * KEY2^1 = H_forb(k=1)

H_forb_1 = 7 = C(7, 1): choose 1 from 7
H_forb_2 = 21 = C(7, 2): choose 2 from 7

Is H_forb(k) = C(7, k+1) for all k?
  k=0: H_forb=     7, C(7,1)=     7, match=True
  k=1: H_forb=    21, C(7,2)=    21, match=True
  k=2: H_forb=    63, C(7,3)=    35, match=False
  k=3: H_forb=   189, C(7,4)=    35, match=False
  k=4: H_forb=   567, C(7,5)=    21, match=False
  k=5: H_forb=  1701, C(7,6)=     7, match=False

No — C(7,3)=35, not 63. Only k=0,1 match.
But note: H_forb_2 = C(7, 2) = T(7, 2) = triangular number


======================================================================
  Part 9: THE FORBIDDEN SEQUENCE AND p-ADIC VALUATION
======================================================================

p-adic valuations of forbidden values 7 * 3^k:

  v_2(H_forb(k)):
    k=0: v_2(7) = 0
    k=1: v_2(21) = 0
    k=2: v_2(63) = 0
    k=3: v_2(189) = 0
    k=4: v_2(567) = 0
    k=5: v_2(1701) = 0

  v_3(H_forb(k)):
    k=0: v_3(7) = 0  = k
    k=1: v_3(21) = 1  = k
    k=2: v_3(63) = 2  = k
    k=3: v_3(189) = 3  = k
    k=4: v_3(567) = 4  = k
    k=5: v_3(1701) = 5  = k

  v_5(H_forb(k)):
    k=0: v_5(7) = 0
    k=1: v_5(21) = 0
    k=2: v_5(63) = 0
    k=3: v_5(189) = 0
    k=4: v_5(567) = 0
    k=5: v_5(1701) = 0

  v_7(H_forb(k)):
    k=0: v_7(7) = 1  = 1 (always)
    k=1: v_7(21) = 1  = 1 (always)
    k=2: v_7(63) = 1  = 1 (always)
    k=3: v_7(189) = 1  = 1 (always)
    k=4: v_7(567) = 1  = 1 (always)
    k=5: v_7(1701) = 1  = 1 (always)

OBSERVATION: v_3(H_forb(k)) = k, v_7(H_forb(k)) = 1 always
  The forbidden sequence has EXACT 3-adic valuation k
  and EXACT 7-adic valuation 1

In the 3-adic integers Z_3:
  H_forb(k) = 7 * 3^k -> 0 as k -> infinity
  The forbidden sequence CONVERGES to 0 in Z_3!

In the 7-adic integers Z_7:
  H_forb(k) = 7 * 3^k = 7 * 3^k
  v_7(H_forb(k)) = 1 for all k, so |H_forb(k)|_7 = 1/7 always
  The forbidden sequence has CONSTANT 7-adic norm!

======================================================================
  Part 10: ROOT SYSTEM DIMENSIONS AND THE (2,3)-CATALAN TRIANGLE
======================================================================

We found: |Phi^+(E_8)| - |Phi^+(E_6)| = 120 - 36 = 84 = T(6; 3, 1)

Let's check ALL differences:
Root count differences:
  |Phi^+(E_7)| - |Phi^+(E_6)| = 63 - 36 = 27
  |Phi^+(E_8)| - |Phi^+(E_6)| = 120 - 36 = 84 = T(6;3,1)
  |Phi^+(E_8)| - |Phi^+(E_7)| = 120 - 63 = 57
  |Phi^+(E_6)| - |Phi^+(F_4)| = 36 - 24 = 12 = T(7;0,3)
  |Phi^+(E_7)| - |Phi^+(F_4)| = 63 - 24 = 39
  |Phi^+(E_8)| - |Phi^+(F_4)| = 120 - 24 = 96
  |Phi^+(E_6)| - |Phi^+(G_2)| = 36 - 6 = 30
  |Phi^+(E_7)| - |Phi^+(G_2)| = 63 - 6 = 57
  |Phi^+(E_8)| - |Phi^+(G_2)| = 120 - 6 = 114
  |Phi^+(F_4)| - |Phi^+(G_2)| = 24 - 6 = 18

Root count sums:
  |Phi^+(E_6)| + |Phi^+(G_2)| = 36+6 = 42
  |Phi^+(F_4)| + |Phi^+(G_2)| = 24+6 = 30

======================================================================
  Part 11: GRAND SYNTHESIS
======================================================================

======================================================================
  THE FORBIDDEN SEQUENCE IS DEEPLY WOVEN INTO ROOT SYSTEMS
======================================================================

1. |Phi^+(E_7)| = 63 = H_forb_3 = 7 * 3^2
   The 3rd forbidden value counts E_7 positive roots!

2. H_forb(k) = Phi_3(2) * 3^k = [3 choose 1]_2 * KEY2^k
   It's a q=2 object scaled by powers of q=3!

3. In the (2,3)-Catalan triangle:
   T(n; n-3, 1) = C(2n-3, n-3)
   At n=5: T(5;2,1) = C(7,2) = 21 = H_forb_2

4. H_forb_1 = 7 = C(7,1), H_forb_2 = 21 = C(7,2)
   The first TWO forbidden values are consecutive binomial
   coefficients from the SAME row (row 7 = H_forb_1)!

5. The Mersenne forbidden values (k even):
   H_forb_0 = 7 = M_3 (exponent KEY2)
   H_forb_2 = 63 = M_6 (exponent h(G2))

6. In Gaussian binomials:
   [3 choose 1]_2 = 7 = H_forb_1
   [6 choose 1]_2 = 63 = H_forb_3 = |Phi^+(E_7)|
   The forbidden values are Mersenne numbers at KEY2 and h(G2)!

7. The Weyl group primes {2,3,5,7} = {KEY1, KEY2, KEY_SUM, H_forb_1}
   H_forb_1 = 7 is the LARGEST prime needed for exceptional Weyl groups!

8. Lattice indices det(Cartan_E_n) = {3, 2, 1} = {KEY2, KEY1, 1}
   descending in n=6,7,8 — a (2,3) countdown to self-duality!

9. The 3-adic world: H_forb(k) -> 0 in Z_3
   The forbidden values become 'invisible' 3-adically!
   This is the p-adic shadow of why they're forbidden in tournaments.
